Boston Beer Appoints Jonathan N. Potter as Its CMOHomeMailFlickrTumblrNewsSportsFinanceCelebrityAnswersGroupsMobileMoreTry Yahoo Finance on Firefox »YahooSearchSearchSign inU.S. Markets closedS&P 5002,475.42-2.41 (-0.10%)Dow 3021,796.55+85.54 (+0.39%)Nasdaq6,382.19-40.56 (-0.63%)Boston Beer Appoints Jonathan N. Potter as Its CMOGabriel KaneMarket RealistJune 28, 2016ReblogShareTweetShareKey Events in the Consumer Sector in the Fourth Week of June(Continued from Prior Part)Price movement Boston Beer Company (SAM) rose by 0.99% and closed at $161.02 per share at the end of the fourth week of June 2016. The stock’s weekly, monthly, and YTD (year-to-date) price movements were 0.99%, 0.27%, and -20.3%, respectively. This means that Boston Beer is trading 1.6% above its 20-day moving average, 1.5% above its 50-day moving average, and 15.7% below its 200-day moving average.Related ETFs and peersThe Vanguard Extended Market ETF (VXF) invests 0.05% of its holdings in Boston Beer. VXF tracks a market-cap-weighted version of the S&P Total Market Index, excluding all S&P 500 stocks. VXF’s YTD price movement was 0.03% on June 24, 2016.The iShares Russell 2000 ETF (IWM) invests 0.15% of its holdings in Boston Beer. IWM tracks a market-cap-weighted index of US small-cap stocks. The index selects stocks ranked 1,001–3,000 by market cap.The market caps of Boston Beer’s competitors are as follows:Constellation Brands (STZ) – $31.1 billionMolson Coors Brewing Company (TAP) – $21.2 billionCompania Cervecerias Unidas S.A.-ADR (CCU) – $4.0 billionBoston Beer’s new CMO Jonathan N. Potter has been appointed as Boston Beer’s CMO starting in August. Potter will oversee its planning and development. He will also be in charge of the execution of brand development, marketing, and advertising initiatives.Performance in fiscal 1Q16Boston Beer reported fiscal 1Q16 net revenue of $188.8 million—a fall of 5.4% compared to net revenue of $199.5 million in fiscal 1Q15. The company’s gross profit margin and operating income fell by 2.8% and 49.3%, respectively, in fiscal 1Q16—compared to the same period the previous year.Its net income and EPS (earnings per share) fell to $7.0 million and $0.53, respectively, in fiscal 1Q16—compared to $13.7 million and $1.00, respectively, in fiscal 1Q16.Boston Beer’s cash and cash equivalents fell by 45.8% and its inventories rose by 9.2% in fiscal 1Q16—compared to fiscal 4Q15. Its current ratio fell to 1.8x in fiscal 1Q16—compared to 2.0x in fiscal 4Q15.ProjectionsThe company made the following projections for fiscal 2016:EPS of $6.50–$7.30gross margin of 51%–53%effective tax rate of ~37%depletion and shipment percentage change of -4%–2%capital spending of $50 million–$70 million to support future growth and product innovation and to drive efficiencies and cost reductionsIn the next part, we’ll look at Kellogg Company.Continue to Next PartBrowse this series on Market Realist:Part 1 - Who Were the Outliers in the Consumer Space at the End of June?Part 3 - Kellogg Establishes Venture Capital to Invest in StartupsPart 4 - Why Did Coca-Cola Invest in Aloe Gloe?ReblogShareTweetShareRecently ViewedYour list is empty.What to Read NextAmazon ploughs ahead with high sales and spending; profit plungesReutersEngineer Finds Pattern; Makes Millions in StocksMoney MorningSponsoredTrump’s unwitting legacy could be universal health coverageYahoo FinanceMarine dog with cancer gets tear-filled farewellAssociated PressNew Battery Tech Could Let Electric Cars Charge in Mere MinutesPopular MechanicsZuckerberg Wife's Ambitious Secret Finally ExposedUNewz.MeSponsoredTwitter is only famous now because of President Trump: NYSE traderYahoo Finance VideoRolls-Royce Motor CEO: We’re not in the auto business. We’re in the luxury business.Yahoo FinanceGOP senators hold press conference to demand assurances that GOP health plan does not become lawBusiness InsiderDiscover it: 4.8 out of 5 avg. by 24K+ customersDiscover CardSponsoredRepublicans kill the border taxYahoo FinanceBuffalo Wild Wings is killing one of customers' favorite dealsBusiness InsiderHouse panel approves legislation to speed deployment of self-driving carsReutersBald Men: This Shampoo Re-Grows Hair Like WildfireShapiroMDSponsoredAmazon could be the first trillion dollar company: NYSE traderYahoo Finance VideoHow grocers feel about Amazon: 'There was a lot of fear before, there's a lot more fear now'Yahoo Finance‘What Happened’: Hillary’s new book isn’t out yet, but Twitter is already making fun of the titlee-nuf-z-nuf: What happened? I will tell you what happened she was a terrible candidate a liar a hater of America a Socialist Progressive who wanted to destroy America from within and our great Constitution. America truly dodged a bullet when she didn't get elected to the Presidency of the United States.She was responsible for the deaths of 4 brave Americans in Libya she did nothing but set by and watch them be brutally murdered. She leaked classified information to our enemies she knowingly used a private server doing all she could to destroy America from within.Her along with her husband Bill Clinton are pure evil I can go on but I thank you understand and get my point.Join the Conversation1 / 5444









